      <p>The tool sums your monthly spend across three highest-cost categories — marketing, inventory, and tracking — then multiplies by twelve for annual exposure. The recovery slider applies a realistic replacement rate: <strong>conservative (50%)</strong> assumes you only swap the obvious overlaps; <strong>aggressive (85%)</strong> assumes you deploy the full free stack but keep one or two genuinely irreplaceable paid tools; <strong>full reset (100%)</strong> assumes every category moves to a free native or Make.com-based alternative. Most stores land in the 85% band, because a small number of tools — advanced SMS, true multi-channel inventory, enterprise loyalty — are worth keeping. The point of the calculator is not to argue every app is waste; it is to separate the spend that buys real differentiated value from the spend that simply duplicates what a webhook and a Google Sheet do for free.</p>

      <h3>Why app bills grow silently</h3>
      <p>App spend is the most under-audited line in most Shopify P&amp;Ls because each individual app feels cheap. A $49 review app and a $99 attribution tool never trigger a budget review on their own — but ten of them compound into a four-figure monthly bill that scales <em>with revenue</em>, since most apps tier their pricing on order volume, contacts, or ad spend. That is the trap: the more successful your store becomes, the more these tools charge, even though the underlying job — fire an event, log a row, send an email — costs nothing to run server-side. Replacing them with a webhook-based stack breaks that link between revenue and tooling cost permanently, which is why the saving compounds rather than staying flat.</p>
